 <title>Migrate from &smt; to &rmt;</title>
 <para>
  This chapter describes the migration from &smt; on &slsa; 12 to &rmt;
  on &slsa; 15.
 </para>
 <sect1 xml:id="sec.rmt_migrate.notes">
  <title>Important Notes</title>
  <warning>
   <title>Read This Section Carefully</title>
   <para>
    Carefully read this section. It contains vital information about
    the migration process.
   </para>
  </warning>
  <variablelist>
   <varlistentry>
    <term>Use New Host</term>
    <listitem>
     <para>
      We recommend that you install &rmt; on a new host. &rmt; is not a
      complete replacement for &smt;. It has a different workflow than
      &smt; and only supports &sls; 12 and newer. However, it is
      technically possible to use the same host for &smt; and &rmt;.
     </para>
    </listitem>
   </varlistentry>
   <varlistentry>
    <term>Repository Settings</term>
    <listitem>
     <para>
      The settings of staged repositories will <emphasis>not</emphasis>
      be exported from &smt;. Repositories that have been marked to be
      mirrored will be exported.
     </para>
    </listitem>
   </varlistentry>
   <varlistentry>
    <term>Custom Repositories</term>
    <listitem>
     <para>
      Disabled custom repositories settings will
      <emphasis>not</emphasis> be exported from &smt;. Enabled custom
      repositories will be exported.
     </para>
    </listitem>
   </varlistentry>
   <varlistentry>
    <term>Expired Subscriptions</term>
    <listitem>
     <para>
      Products no longer available on the organization subscriptions
      will not be available on &rmt;.
     </para>
    </listitem>
   </varlistentry>
   <varlistentry>
    <term>Client Information</term>
    <listitem>
     <para>
      Systems and their activated products will be exported. &smt;
      client jobs and patch status will not be exported from &smt;.
     </para>
    </listitem>
   </varlistentry>
  </variablelist>
